UNDIAGNOSED DEATHS, SWINE - LITHUANIA: WILD BOAR, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
*************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 13 Jan 2014
Source: ru.DELFI.lt, GRYNAS.lt [in Russian, machine transl., summ., edited]
http://ru.delfi.lt/news/live/ohotniki-podozrevayut-chto-chuma-svinej-dobralas-do-litvy.d?id=63743638


According to hunters in the Alytus region [county], massive mortality of wild boars has been observed. The hunters believe that the reason for this phenomenon is swine fever, coming to Lithuania from Belarus. Moreover, hunters accuse government agencies of hiding the appearance of the disease in Lithuania. The State Food and Veterinary Service (GPVS) claims that swine fever is not present in Lithuania.

One hunter said boar deaths have been recorded since last summer [2013]. "Now," he says, "there are already dead boar in additional areas, for example in Salcininkai" [a city in Vilnius county, south east Lithuania, near the border with Belarus].

Another interviewee told GRYNAS.lt that dead boars were found in Dzukija [Alytus county, site of a national park] since November 2013. According to him, during this period about 40 dead wild boar were found. The man said that the outward signs resemble African swine fever. According to his observations, most boars were found in the woods of Varchos, Kalesnikay, and Gediminas.

However, the chairman of Alytus's community of hunters and fishermen, Evaldas Daynauskas, told GRYNAS.lt that the situation should not be dramatised. He did not deny the fact of unexplained mortality of boars in the Alytus region, but argued that studies have not confirmed suspicions of plague.

According to the representative of GPVS, inspector Marius Masiulis, laboratory studies have not confirmed swine plague. "We always respond to calls and collect samples, but laboratory studies do not suggest that this is plague; the cause of mortality has not been established." He expressed hope that the cause of boar death will be clarified soon.

[byline: Thomas Janonis]

